definition.value: A river in southeastern Massachusetts in the United States. It arises from the confluence of the Town River and Matfield River, in the town of Bridgewater. From there it meanders through the towns of Halifax, Middleborough and Raynham, through the city of Taunton for which it is named, the towns of Berkley, Dighton, Somerset, and the Assonet section of Freetown, to Fall River where it joins Mount Hope Bay, an arm of Narragansett Bay.
A river draining into Summer Lake.

A river on the Pacific coast of northwest Oregon in the United States, approximately 34 km long. It drains a timber-producing area of the Northern Oregon Coast Range northwest of Portland. It forms the first estuary south of the mouth of the Columbia River along the Oregon Coast. The Necanicum River rises south of Humbug Mountain and enters the Pacific Ocean at Seaside.

A river on the Pacific coast of northwest Oregon in the United States, approximately 192 km long. It drains part of the Northern Oregon Coast Range northwest of Portland, originating on the east side of the mountains and flowing in a loop around the north end of the range near the mouth Columbia River. It rises in the northeast corner of Tillamook County, in the Tillamook State Forest. It initially flows northeast, across the northwest corner of Washington County and into western Columbia County, past Vernonia and Pittsburg. At Pittsburg, it looks to the northwest and west into Clatsop County, then flows southwest back into northern Tillamook County. It enters Nehalem Bay on the Pacific in an estuary at Nehalem, about 110 km west-northwest of Portland.

A river on the coast of northwest Oregon in the United States. It drains a mountainous timber-producing region of the Northern Oregon Coast Range west of Portland into Pacific Ocean. It rises in northern Tillamook County in the Tillamook State Forest and flows southwest, entering the north end of Tillamook Bay approximately 3 km east of Garibaldi.

A river on the coast of northwest Oregon in the United States. It drains a mountainous timber-producing region in the Northern Oregon Coast Range west of Portland. It rises in two forks northern Tillamook County in the Tillamook State Forest northeast of Bay City. The North Fork and South Fork, each 8 km long, flow west before joining. The combined river flows southwest, entering the southeast end of Tillamook Bay approximately 6 km northwest of the town of Tillamook.

A river in the coast of northwest Oregon in the United States. It rises in several forks in the Tillamook State Forest in the mountains of northeastern Tillamook County. The North Fork (approximately 16 km long) rises in northern Tillamook County and flows south. The South Fork rises in eastern Tillamook County and flows west, receiving the Devils Lake Fork and joining the North Fork near Lee's Camp. The combined river flows southwest to Tillamook, entering the southeast end of Tillamook Bay approximately 5 km northwest of Tillamook.

A river on the coast of northwest Oregon in the United States. It drains an oceanside valley in the foothills of the Northern Oregon Coast Range west of Portland, discharging to the Pacific Ocean via Tillamook Bay. It rises in southern Tillamook County in the Siuslaw National Forest, approximately 6 km from the ocean, due east of Cape Lookout. It flows initially east, then generally north, through a long broadening farming valley, passing west of Tillamook and entering the south end of Tillamook Bay. For its lower 1.6 km, it shares a channel with the Trask River.

A river in northwestern Oregon in the United States. It drains a mountainous timber-producing area of the Northern Oregon Coast Range west of Portland into the Pacific Ocean. It rises in two forks. The North Fork (48 km long), rises in several forks itself in the Tillamook State Forest in western Washington County west of Forest Grove, Oregon. It flows generally west into eastern Tillamook County. The South Fork (16 km long) rises in southern Tillamook County and flows north. The two forks join in central Tillamook County and the combined stream flows west, past Tillamook, entering the south end of Tillamook Bay on the Pacific northwest of the Tillamook. For its last 1.6 km it forms a common channel with the Tillamook River.

A river on the Pacific coast of northwest Oregon in the United States. It drains an area of the Central Oregon Coast Range west of the Willamette Valley. It rises in the Van Duzer State Forest in northwestern Polk County, in the mountains west of Salem. It flows generally northwest, through Siuslaw National Forest and enters Nestucca Bay on the Pacific near Pacific City.

A short coastal river, approximately 32 km long, on the Pacific coast of northwest Oregon in the United States. It drains a forested region of the Coastal Range along the coast near Lincoln City. It rises in the mountains east of Lincoln City and west of Dallas along the Lincoln-Polk county line. It flows generally WSW, long the border between Lincoln and Tillamook counties, through the Van Duzer State Forest and the Siuslaw National Forest. It enters the Pacific approximately 6.4 km north of Lincoln City on the Tillamook-Lincoln county line.
A river in Lincoln City, Oregon, United States. The river flows from Devils Lake, under US Route 101, and into the Pacific Ocean, entirely within the city limits of Lincoln City.

A river on the Pacific coast of Oregon in the United States. It rises in a remote area of western Polk County and flows southwest, to Siletz, then generally northwest towards the coast. It enters the Pacific through Siletz Bay south of Lincoln City.

A river on the Pacific coast of Oregon in the United States. It drains an area of the Central Oregon Coast Range west of the Willamette Valley near Newport. It rises in the mountains west of Corvalllis, in the Siuslaw National Forest along the county line between Benton and Lincoln counties. It flows south, then generally west, in a highly serpentine course, past Toledo. It enters the Pacific in Yaquina Bay, a broad estuary at Newport.

A river that flows fom Alsea, an unincorporated community in the coastal mountains of the State of Oregon, to the Pacific Ocean near the city of Waldport. It begins at the confluence of the North Fork Alsea River and the South Fork Alsea River and ends in Alsea Bay, a wide estuary at Waldport. The river flows generally west-northwest in a winding course through the mountains of southern Benton and Lincoln counties, passing near the unincorporated community of Tidewater and through the Siuslaw National Forest.

A short river on the central Oregon coast, about 100 km west-north-west of Eugene. The river begins about 19 km east-south-east of Yachats, Oregon in steep, thick forest, a half mile north of Klickatat Mountain and flows northward about 5 km, joins Grass Creek then about 640 m later joins with School Fork and turns westward. Keller Creek and Stump Creek join after about a 1.6 km of meandering, followed after a 800 m by Neiglick Creek at river km 16. The river bed widens significantly and levels out to become very slow moving and turns northward about a half mile, then westward at rriver km 13. It meanders westward the rest of the way to the ocean.

A river along the Pacific coast of Oregon in the United States. It drains an area of approximately 11900 km2 in the Central Oregon Coast Range southwest of the Willamette Valley and north of the watershed of the Umpqua River. It rises in the Coastal Range of southwestern Lane County, approximately 8 km west of Cottage Grove. It flows generally WNW through the mountains, past Swisshome, entering the Pacific at Florence.

A river that flows for about 8.9 km into Coos Bay along the Pacific coast of southwest Oregon in the United States. Formed by the confluence of its major tributaries, the South Fork Coos River and the Millicoma River.

A river in southwestern Oregon in the United States. It rises in several forks in the Coastal Range, formed at Myrtle Point by the confluence of its North and South Forks. The North Fork (68 km long) rises in northern Coos County and flows southwest. The East Fork (48 km long) rises in western Douglas County, approximately 24 km southwest of Roseburg, and flows generally west into Coos County, where it joins the North Fork. The South Fork (103 km long) rises in southern Coos County, north of the Wild Rogue Wilderness Area, and flows briefly southwest, then turns north. It receives the Middle Fork (64 km long) then joins the North Fork from the south at Myrtle Point. The combined river flows in zigzag generally west, past Coquille. It enters the Pacific at Bandon, approximately 32 km north of Cape Blanco.

A short river on the southern Oregon coast. It begins at Floras Lake and runs northward (almost NNE) to the Pacific Ocean a distance of approximately 16 river km flowing parallel to the ocean behind the foredune. It is located about 8 miles south of Bandon, Oregon and 12 miles north of Cape Blanco.

A river in southwestern Oregon in the United States. It rises in the mountains of northern Curry County, south of Sugarloaf Mountain in the Siskiyou National Forest. It flows generally west, through Grassy Knob Wilderness, the town of Sixes, and eventually enters the Pacific just north of Cape Blanco. The mouth of the river is along the coast in Cape Blanco State Park.

A river rising in the mountains in northern Curry County, in the Siskiyou National Forest. The river initially flows generally west, through the Grassy Knob Wilderness. It then flows northwest, approaching the coast north of Port Orford and entering the Pacific between Cape Blanco to the north and The Heads to the south.
A river.

A river in southwestern Oregon in the United States. It rises in southern Curry County in the Kalmiopsis Wilderness, northwest of Chetco Peak in the Coastal Range. It flows northwest, passing west of Pearsol Peak, then southwest, passing between Mount Emily (south) and Bosley Butte (north). It empties into the Pacific Ocean at Brookings, approximately 8 km north of the California state line.
A river.

A short river in the southern region of the State of Oregon, and part of the Klamath Basin drainage. The Wood River flows through Klamath County, Oregon with headwaters emanating from a large natural spring located in Jackson F. Kimball State Recreation Site. The Wood River meanders through pine forest and agricultural land for 29 km before flowing into Agency Lake.

A river in the northwest part of the State of Washington. After the Middle and South Forks join, the combined river flows northwest, emerging from the mountains and flowing past Everson and Lynden. Near Everson, the river is at risk of floods breaching the right bank, allowing flow into lower lands to the north, through Sumas River and into Canada. At Lynden the river turns southwest and then, near Ferndale, south, to enter the north side of Bellingham Bay at the Lummi Indian Reservation, approximately 4.8 km west of Bellingham.

A river in northwestern Washington in the United States. The river drains an area of 360 km2 between the Skagit River basin on the south and the Nooksack River basin on the north. The Samish River originates on a low divide in Whatcom County, and its tributary, Friday Creek, originates in the hills south of Bellingham. The river continues its southwesterly flow through Skagit County and outlets into Samish Bay in Puget Sound.

A river that originates at the toe of the Pemberton Icefield. Shortly below the glacier, the river collects several more glacier fed tributaries as it flows south. About 21.8 km southwest of its source, the Squamish meets the Elaho River, which is one of its two largest tributaries. After its confluence with the Elaho, the river moves southeast for another 24.8 km until its confluence with the Ashlu River. Another 16.4 km from there the river is met by the Cheakamus River, and 4.7 km further south, the Mamquam River. From there, the river flows another 6 km to its mouth at the head of the Howe Sound.

A river that springs near Lady Evelyn-Smoothwater Provincial Park in the Timiskaming District in Ontario, Canada. It flows in a south-easterly direction through Sudbury and Nipissing Districts before it empties at the north shore of and into Lake Nipissing.

A river. A tributary of the Naches River. It begins in two forks, the North Fork Tieton River and South Fork Tieton River. The North Fork originates at McCall Glacier on the eastern sides of Old Snowy Mountain, Ives Peak, and the Goat Rocks. Collecting headwater streams from other high mountains such as Tieton Peak, the North Fork flows northeast into Clear Lake, then into the west end of Rimrock Lake. The South Fork Tieton River begins at Meade Glacier on the eastern side of Gilbert Peak, also part of the Goat Rocks. The South Fork collects many streams as it flows generally north, entering Rimrock Lake near its east end.

A river, approximately 48 km long, in western Washington, the United States. It empties into Willapa Bay, the first large estuary on the Washington coast north of the Columbia River. The river rises in the Willapa Hills in northeastern Pacific County and flows northwest into Grays Harbor County. The river turns southwest where it is crossed by US 101, reenters Pacific County, and reaches Willapa Bay at State Route 105, twelve miles northwest of Raymond.

A river on the Pacific coast of southwestern Washington in the United States, approximately 32 km long. It drains an area of low hills and a coastal plain into Willapa Bay, a large estuary north of the mouth of the Columbia River. The river rises in the Willapa Hills in southeastern Pacific County, approximately 40 km west of Chehalis. It flows northwest in a winding course past the small communities of Willapa and Raymond. It enters the northwest end of Willapa Bay at South Bend.
A river that originates in the Willapa Hills and flows generally west, passing the community of Naselle before discharging to the southern part of Willapa Bay.

A river that originates in the hills of the southwestern part of Washington, close to the source of the North Fork Palix River. It flows generally west, discharging to Willapa Bay near Bay Center just north of the Niawiakum River.

A river that originates in the hills of the southwestern part of Washington. It flows generally west, discharging to Willapa Bay near Bay Center and the mouth of the Palix River. The river's entire length is only a few miles. The lower half of the Niawiakum River is a broad estuary and tidal marshland.
A river that rises in the Willapa Hills in Pacific County. It flows generally west to Willapa Bay, an estuary of the Pacific Ocean.
A river that originates just north of the mouth of the Columbia River in the Bear River Range and Willapa Hills. It flows generally north and west, discharging to the southern end of Willapa Bay.
A river emptying in Willapa Bay.
A river emptying in Willapa Bay.
A river emptying in Willapa Bay.
A river emptying in Willapa Bay.
A river in Grays Harbor County, Washington, in the United States. The Humptulips River originates in the Olympic National Forest in the East Fork and West Fork.

A river. It has three main tributaries, the East Fork, West Fork, and Middle Fork Hoquiam Rivers. The main stem Hoquiam River is formed by the confluence of the West and East Forks. The Middle Fork is a tributary of the West Fork. The Hoquiam River rises in Grays Harbor County. It flows generally south to Hoquiam, where it empties into Grays Harbor, an estuary of the Pacific Ocean.

A river in Washington in the United States. It originates in several forks in southwestern Washington, flows east, then north, then west, in a large curve, before discharging to Grays Harbor, an estuary of the Pacific Ocean.
A river discharging to Grays Harbor.
A river discharging to Grays Harbor.
A river draining to the Pacific Ocean.

A river draining to the Pacific Ocean. Both the Moclips River and its main tributary, the North Fork Moclips River, originate on the slopes of Macafee Hill. Both flow generally west. The North Fork joins the main river about 3.2 km from the Pacific Ocean. The Moclips River empties into the Pacific near Moclips.

A river located on the Olympic Peninsula in the State of Washington. It originates deep in the Olympic Mountains in the Olympic National Park. Several miles above Lake Quinault the river is joined by its main tributary, the North Fork Quinault River. The main Quinault River above this confluence is sometimes called the East Fork Quinault River. Below the confluence the river marks the boundary of Olympic National Park for several miles before discharging to Lake Quinault. After the lake, the Quinault River flows southwest, reaching the Pacific at Taholah. From Lake Quinault to the ocean, the river is contained within the Quinault Indian Reservation.
